




TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Deterrent Effect of Antitrust Enforcement
AU  - Block, Michael Kent
AU  - Nold, Frederick Carl
AU  - Sidak, Joseph Gregory
Y1  - 1981/06/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260979
DO  - 10.1086/260979
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 429
EP  - 445
VL  - 89
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In this paper we formulate and test a model of collusive pricing in the presence of antitrust enforcement. We show that a cartel's optimal price is likely to be neither the competitive price nor the price that the cartel would set in the absence of antitrust enforcement but rather an intermediate price that depends on the levels of antitrust enforcement efforts and penalties. Our empirical results reveal that increasing antitrust enforcement in the presence of a credible threat of large damage awards has the deterrent effect of reducing mark-ups in the bread industry.
AB  - In this paper we formulate and test a model of collusive pricing in the presence of antitrust enforcement. We show that a cartel's optimal price is likely to be neither the competitive price nor the price that the cartel would set in the absence of antitrust enforcement but rather an intermediate price that depends on the levels of antitrust enforcement efforts and penalties. Our empirical results reveal that increasing antitrust enforcement in the presence of a credible threat of large damage awards has the deterrent effect of reducing mark-ups in the bread industry.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260979
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260979
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Market Evaluation of Human Capital: The Case of Indentured Servitude
AU  - Galenson, David W.
Y1  - 1981/06/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260980
DO  - 10.1086/260980
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 446
EP  - 467
VL  - 89
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines the market for human capital created by the institution of indentured servitude in colonial America. The indenture system allowed English emigrants to obtain passage to the colonies by selling claims on their future labor. With the size of the debt approximately equal for all emigrants, the length of the term for which a servant was bound is predicted to have varied inversely with expected productivity in the colonies. Analysis of two collections of contracts made in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries supports the prediction. Age, skill, and literacy were negatively related to length of indenture. Women received shorter terms than men at young ages, while servants bound for the West Indies and those bound in periods of high colonial demand for labor also received reductions.
AB  - This paper examines the market for human capital created by the institution of indentured servitude in colonial America. The indenture system allowed English emigrants to obtain passage to the colonies by selling claims on their future labor. With the size of the debt approximately equal for all emigrants, the length of the term for which a servant was bound is predicted to have varied inversely with expected productivity in the colonies. Analysis of two collections of contracts made in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries supports the prediction. Age, skill, and literacy were negatively related to length of indenture. Women received shorter terms than men at young ages, while servants bound for the West Indies and those bound in periods of high colonial demand for labor also received reductions.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260980
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260980
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Welfare Cost of Capital Income Taxation in a Growing Economy
AU  - Chamley, Christophe
Y1  - 1981/06/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260981
DO  - 10.1086/260981
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 468
EP  - 496
VL  - 89
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The welfare cost of capital income taxation is analyzed in a general equilibrium framework, where the private sector is represented by a competitive household endowed with perfect foresight and an infinite life. The value of the welfare cost depends essentially on the elasticity of substitution between capital and labor in the production function. Numerical estimates are presented for different values of the parameters of the model. The welfare gain obtained by the abolition of the capital income tax is smaller when the private sector is not endowed with perfect foresight (it is reduced by about 40 percent when expectations are myopic). The allocation efficiency cost of the corporate tax dwarfs the intertemporal welfare cost.
AB  - The welfare cost of capital income taxation is analyzed in a general equilibrium framework, where the private sector is represented by a competitive household endowed with perfect foresight and an infinite life. The value of the welfare cost depends essentially on the elasticity of substitution between capital and labor in the production function. Numerical estimates are presented for different values of the parameters of the model. The welfare gain obtained by the abolition of the capital income tax is smaller when the private sector is not endowed with perfect foresight (it is reduced by about 40 percent when expectations are myopic). The allocation efficiency cost of the corporate tax dwarfs the intertemporal welfare cost.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260981
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260981
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Foreign Ownership and the Theory of Trade and Welfare
AU  - Brecher, Richard A.
AU  - Bhagwati, Jagdish N.
Y1  - 1981/06/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260982
DO  - 10.1086/260982
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 497
EP  - 511
VL  - 89
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Some standard topics in the theory of international trade are reconsidered in this paper by distinguishing between national and aggregate income when fixed supplies of foreign inputs are present within the home country. Under conditions that would ensure a national welfare gain if foreign ownership were absent, international transfer, economic growth, or tariff policy might cause a national welfare loss in the presence of foreign ownership. The techniques developed could be applied to other domestic distinctions (such as those based on race, sex, age, or ethnicity) and to the theory of customs unions in a three-country world.
AB  - Some standard topics in the theory of international trade are reconsidered in this paper by distinguishing between national and aggregate income when fixed supplies of foreign inputs are present within the home country. Under conditions that would ensure a national welfare gain if foreign ownership were absent, international transfer, economic growth, or tariff policy might cause a national welfare loss in the presence of foreign ownership. The techniques developed could be applied to other domestic distinctions (such as those based on race, sex, age, or ethnicity) and to the theory of customs unions in a three-country world.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260982
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260982
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Accounting for Price Changes: American Steel Rails, 1879-1910
AU  - Allen, Robert C.
Y1  - 1981/06/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260983
DO  - 10.1086/260983
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 512
EP  - 528
VL  - 89
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A framework is developed for decomposing product price changes into changes in input prices, technical efficiency, and deviations of price from unit cost. This framework facilitates the measurement of productivity growth in noncompetitive industries. The history of American steel rail prices between 1879 and 1910 is analyzed, and it is concluded (in contrast with much recent work) that productivity growth remained rapid until the twentieth century and that the steel industry was sufficiently collusive so that the rail producers received the benefits of that productivity growth as excess profits.
AB  - A framework is developed for decomposing product price changes into changes in input prices, technical efficiency, and deviations of price from unit cost. This framework facilitates the measurement of productivity growth in noncompetitive industries. The history of American steel rail prices between 1879 and 1910 is analyzed, and it is concluded (in contrast with much recent work) that productivity growth remained rapid until the twentieth century and that the steel industry was sufficiently collusive so that the rail producers received the benefits of that productivity growth as excess profits.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260983
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260983
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Some Evidence on Cross-Sector Effects of the Minimum Wage
AU  - Tauchen, George E.
Y1  - 1981/06/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260984
DO  - 10.1086/260984
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 529
EP  - 547
VL  - 89
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper tests Mincer's minimum-wage model by estimating reduced-form wage and employment equations for both the covered and uncovered sectors in nine regions of the United States. As theory predicts, in regions with comparatively small covered-sector demand elasticities, the northern and midwestern regions, the uncovered-sector wage increases after a minimum-wage hike; and in regions with comparatively large demand elasticities, the southern and western regions, the uncovered-sector wage decreases. Because of data limitations the uncovered-sector employment effect could not be estimated sharply, and so its relationship to the covered-sector demand elasticity is weak.
AB  - This paper tests Mincer's minimum-wage model by estimating reduced-form wage and employment equations for both the covered and uncovered sectors in nine regions of the United States. As theory predicts, in regions with comparatively small covered-sector demand elasticities, the northern and midwestern regions, the uncovered-sector wage increases after a minimum-wage hike; and in regions with comparatively large demand elasticities, the southern and western regions, the uncovered-sector wage decreases. Because of data limitations the uncovered-sector employment effect could not be estimated sharply, and so its relationship to the covered-sector demand elasticity is weak.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260984
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260984
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Taxes, Inflation, and the Durability of Capital
AU  - Abel, Andrew B.
Y1  - 1981/06/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260985
DO  - 10.1086/260985
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 548
EP  - 560
VL  - 89
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The choice of capital durability is affected by the rate of inflation because nominal depreciation deductions are based on historical cost rather than replacement cost. This paper analyzes a model with competitive firms and demonstrates that an increase in the rate of inflation will lead to an increase in the durability of capital, if the ratio of the nominal discount rate to the rate of depreciation exceeds a critical value. However, if this ratio is less than the crucial value, this effect is reversed. The effect of costs of adjustments on the crucial value is analyzed.
AB  - The choice of capital durability is affected by the rate of inflation because nominal depreciation deductions are based on historical cost rather than replacement cost. This paper analyzes a model with competitive firms and demonstrates that an increase in the rate of inflation will lead to an increase in the durability of capital, if the ratio of the nominal discount rate to the rate of depreciation exceeds a critical value. However, if this ratio is less than the crucial value, this effect is reversed. The effect of costs of adjustments on the crucial value is analyzed.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260985
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260985
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Uncertain Lifetime, Consumption, and Dissaving in Retirement
AU  - Davies, James B.
Y1  - 1981/06/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260986
DO  - 10.1086/260986
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 561
EP  - 577
VL  - 89
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper asks whether the continued accumulation, or mild dissaving, observed among the retired can be explained by uncertain lifetime. In the absence of annuities, after an initial period influenced by borrowing constraints, under constant relative risk aversion, uncertain lifetime depresses consumption by a proportion increasing with age if the elasticity of intertemporal substitution in consumption is "small." Illustrative computations, based on actual income and survival data, show that plausible elasticities are sufficiently small to give this effect. The reduction in consumption is large enough to explain much of the lack of decumulation by the elderly.
AB  - This paper asks whether the continued accumulation, or mild dissaving, observed among the retired can be explained by uncertain lifetime. In the absence of annuities, after an initial period influenced by borrowing constraints, under constant relative risk aversion, uncertain lifetime depresses consumption by a proportion increasing with age if the elasticity of intertemporal substitution in consumption is "small." Illustrative computations, based on actual income and survival data, show that plausible elasticities are sufficiently small to give this effect. The reduction in consumption is large enough to explain much of the lack of decumulation by the elderly.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260986
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260986
Y2  - 2024/03/22
